  "text": "The Apache Kafka codebase contains comprehensive ACL (Access Control List) authorization logic organized across three main packages. In the clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/server/authorizer/ directory, the core interface and supporting types are defined: Authorizer (the main pluggable interface), AuthorizerServerInfo (runtime metadata interface), Action (authorization action class), AuthorizableRequestContext (request context interface), AuthorizationResult (result type), AclCreateResult, and AclDeleteResult classes. These define the public contract for authorizer implementations.\n\nThe metadata/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/metadata/authorizer/ directory contains the built-in implementation: ClusterMetadataAuthorizer extends the base Authorizer interface and defines cluster-aware ACL operations, while StandardAuthorizer implements ClusterMetadataAuthorizer and provides the production-ready authorizer that stores ACLs in the metadata log. Supporting classes in this package include StandardAuthorizerData (data container), AclCache, AclMutator (interface for ACL mutations), StandardAcl, StandardAclWithId, and StandardAclRecordIterator.\n\nThe server/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/security/authorizer/ directory provides utility classes: AclEntry (data class for ACL entries) and AuthorizerUtils (factory utility for creating authorizer instances). This separation allows the core authorization interfaces to be lightweight in the clients module while the metadata module provides the full implementation, and the server module provides operational utilities."
}

